{[show NS]
[ROLE leader][STAGE pre-lead]
Lead the \C7. With no safe singleton or sequence to lead, a low card from your long club suit is the normal start.

[ROLE declarer][STAGE auction-end]
You are in 4\S. Trumps are good for six, and your side tricks come from the \HA, \DA and the \D suit where AQ7x faces T8xx missing the king. NS hold 24 of the 40, leaving the defence 16. The safe play in diamonds is to cash the \DA rather than finesse - a bare king drops and you never lose the lead.

[ROLE declarer][STAGE post-lead]
West led the \C7, which looks like a low card from length rather than a singleton - win it in dummy. Draw trumps, picking up the missing ten, then play the \DA first instead of finessing. The finesse could lose the lead to the hand over your queen; the ace instead drops a singleton king for free, and the diamonds add the trick you need. Trumps, the two red aces and the diamonds bring you to ten.

[ROLE declarer][STAGE post-play]
The diamond order won it - ace before the finesse - catching the bare king and keeping the danger hand off lead. Precisely the safety play to remember.}
