{[show NS]
[ROLE leader][STAGE pre-lead] Lead the \H4. With a five-card heart suit headed by broken honours, fourth-best is the standard attacking lead.

[ROLE declarer][STAGE auction-end] I'm in 4\S with ten cards in trumps between us. The \HA is one trick, dummy's long clubs (KQJ64) give me three winners once the ace is knocked out, and I have AQ76 of diamonds opposite 9542 for two more led by the ace, so ten is comfortable. The thing to handle right is diamonds: cashing the \DA guards against a singleton king rather than finessing into the danger hand. With the trumps solid and clubs to set up, I don't need to gamble the diamond finesse.

[ROLE declarer][STAGE post-lead] West led the \H4, which looks like a fourth-best, so it rates to be from a five-card suit; I win the \HA. NS hold 24 of the 40, leaving only 16 for the defence, and since neither opponent bid, no one is hiding a big hand. I draw trumps, force out the club ace to set up dummy's long clubs, and when I play diamonds I cash the \DA rather than finessing, so a bare king cannot escape. That brings home eleven: five trumps, the \HA, the diamond ace, three clubs, plus a diamond length trick.

[ROLE declarer][STAGE post-play] The safe play was to cash the diamond ace instead of finessing toward the danger hand; with the contract never in doubt, dropping a possible singleton king costs nothing and avoids handing the lead to the wrong defender. Nicely judged, taking the sure line over the flashy one.}
