{[show NS]
[ROLE leader][STAGE pre-lead]
Lead the \CJ. Top of your club sequence is the natural attacking lead and keeps your honours working together.

[ROLE declarer][STAGE auction-end]
You are in 4\S. Trumps are missing the QJT so expect to lose a trump trick, and the \D suit is your trick source: AQxx opposite JTx needs the king to behave. NS hold 23 of the 40, so the defence has 17 - and East did act, so the high cards may sit over you. Plan to cash the \DA rather than risk a finesse into the danger hand: with the king bare offside it drops, and you keep control.

[ROLE declarer][STAGE post-lead]
West led the \CJ, which looks like top of a sequence - win it in dummy. Start trumps; you will likely concede one round to the missing honours, but that is fine. For diamonds, do not finesse: cash the \DA, because if the finesse lost, the hand over your queen would be in to cash its long suit, whereas the ace first drops a singleton king with no risk. Take your established diamonds and the established clubs in dummy, and ten tricks come home.

