{[show NS]
[ROLE leader][STAGE pre-lead]
Lead the \H4. With nothing better to attack, fourth-best from your longest suit is the natural lead.

[ROLE declarer][STAGE auction-end]
You are in 5\S. Trumps are missing the queen but still good for several tricks, and your winners come from the \HA, \DA, the long \D suit and dummy's strong \C suit; diamonds are AQJ7x opposite xxx missing the king. NS hold 25 of the 40, leaving the defence 15. The safe handling of diamonds is to cash the \DA rather than finesse - a bare king drops and you keep the lead.

[ROLE declarer][STAGE post-lead]
West led the \H4, which looks like fourth-best - win the \HA. Draw trumps, allowing for the missing queen, then play the \DA before any finesse. The finesse could hand the lead to the hand over your queen; the ace instead drops a singleton king for free, and the diamonds plus dummy's clubs supply the rest. The tricks add up to eleven, just what you need.

[ROLE declarer][STAGE post-play]
The diamond order was the key - ace first, not the finesse - dropping the bare king while keeping the danger hand off lead. That is the Rabbi's Rule, applied cleanly.}
